### m&#95;Deferred() {#a53fc7d443cf6412add6dfddd11652e5d}

  labels = {["inline"]}>
Like <a href="#a2d9861feadd3a09792967a012559e7b2">m&#95;Specific()</a>, but works if the specific value to match is determined as part of the same <a href="#a25d956d9e0beadd47ce4bc255dfa811d">match()</a> expression.

For example: m&#95;Add(m&#95;Value(X), m&#95;Specific(X)) is incorrect, because <a href="#a2d9861feadd3a09792967a012559e7b2">m&#95;Specific()</a> will bind X before the pattern match starts. m&#95;Add(m&#95;Value(X), m&#95;Deferred(X)) is correct, and will check against whichever value m&#95;Value(X) populated.

  labels = {["inline"]}>
Match an &#39;ordered&#39; floating point maximum function.

Floating point has one special value &#39;NaN&#39;. Therefore, there is no total order. However, if we can ignore the &#39;NaN&#39; value (for example, because of a &#39;no-nans-float-math&#39; flag) a combination of a fcmp and select has &#39;maximum&#39; semantics. In the presence of &#39;NaN&#39; we have to preserve the original select(fcmp(ogt/ge, L, R), L, R) semantics matched by this predicate. <CodeBlock>                    max(L, R)  iff L and R are not NaN
</CodeBlock> m&#95;OrdFMax(L, R) = R iff L or R are NaN

  labels = {["inline"]}>
Match an &#39;unordered&#39; floating point maximum function.

Floating point has one special value &#39;NaN&#39;. Therefore, there is no total order. However, if we can ignore the &#39;NaN&#39; value (for example, because of a &#39;no-nans-float-math&#39; flag) a combination of a fcmp and select has &#39;maximum&#39; semantics. In the presence of &#39;NaN&#39; we have to preserve the original select(fcmp(ugt/ge, L, R), L, R) semantics matched by this predicate. <CodeBlock>                    max(L, R)  iff L and R are not NaN
</CodeBlock> m&#95;UnordFMax(L, R) = L iff L or R are NaN
